A smile and a stick will see you through

Before Bond, a spy didn't need a fancy gadget from Q to get out of trouble.=
=20
John Fisher's Gentleman Spies tells of a golden era in espionage

Giles Foden
Saturday August 10, 2002
The Guardian

Gentleman Spies: Intelligence Agents in the British Empire and Beyond
by John Fisher
209pp, Sutton, =A320
"Supposing they had got some tremendous sacred sanction - some holy thing,=
=20
some book or gospel or some new prophet from the desert, something which=20
would cast over the whole ugly mechanism of German war the glamour of the=20
old torrential raids which crumpled the Byzantine Empire and shook the=20
walls of Vienna? Islam is a fighting creed, and the mullah still stands in=
=20
the pulpit with the Koran in one hand and a drawn sword in the other.=20
Supposing there is some Ark of the Covenant which will madden the remotest=
=20
Moslem peasant with dreams of Paradise? What then, my friend?"
So Richard Hannay, late of The Thirty-Nine Steps, is sent on the perilous=20
mission of Greenmantle, John Buchan's first-world-war thriller. Published=20
in 1916, it raised the spectre of a jihad led by an evil genius bent on=20
thwarting the interests of the so-called civilised nations. That jihad (in=
=20
fact, a genuine part of a German strategy to destabilise British=20
possessions in the east), in combination with the "great game" of the Hindu=
=20
Kush (in which Russian influence was the danger), were the two main=20
concerns of the "gentleman spies" whose stories John Fisher tells in this=20
entertaining and well-informed history.
They were people like the Whittall family, Turkish-speaking Harrovians with=
=20
"major interests in the mohair trade in Asia Minor", the "moneyed tramp"=20
William John Childs, and "the reporter who played the piano" - and kept a=20
snake in a cigar box - Paul Dukes.
Another was Robert (later Baron) Baden-Powell, who wrote an essay on the=20
value of stupidity in spying. While Germany's clever spies were rounded up,=
=20
"the exceedingly stupid Englishmen who wandered about foreign countries=20
sketching cathedrals, or catching butterflies, or fishing for trout, were=20
merely laughed at as harmless lunatics". As for tradecraft, Baden-Powell=20
added that "a smile and a stick will carry you through any difficulty" -=20
sentiments which could just as easily be found in any pre-war spy novel.
By the time Ian Fleming updated the image (and technology) of the gentleman=
=20
spy in the figure of James Bond, real-life spies had been taking their cue=
=20
from fictional avatars for decades. Yet not all the work of these intrepid=
=20
young adventurers had the adrenaline levels of a Buchan-style thriller.=20
Take the case of one Bradshawe, our man in Kirkuk. Styled by friends as=20
"the most bored man in Iraq", he spent his time "resigning by every mail".
Posted by our man in=20
Victoria,pr.http://books.guardian.co.uk/reviews/history/0,6121,771296,00.htm=
l
Where are the Philbies and Hanssens of yesteryear?
Have to keep spellchecking that with Google.
